[metadata]
title: This Little Device Is Better Than a Gimbal.
channel: @octopusinc_
source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N5eRJb4tMS8
upload_date: 20260330
transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you\'re a beginner filmmaker, one of the biggest things to learn is to get stable images. And that can be done in a lot of ways. You can use a tripod, you can use a gimbal, but often times beginners will just grab a camera and start holding it out in front of them and shooting whatever it is that they'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to shoot. But that often results in some micro jitters and some pretty shaky footage. And so a lot of people will go with cameras that have IBIS or use electronic stabilization. But those two have some drawbacks. [music] And so there\'s a different way to'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stabilize your footage that I think might be the best possible way to do it. And that\'s with gyro data. Now, for people who have something like a Canon C50 that has gyro data built'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into their actual video files. But for everyone else, I have the NeeYan gyroscope [music] stabilizer. This little device might just change your life. So I recently made a video on this'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'channel comparing [music] the IBIS in the Panasonic S12, which is filming right now, and the electronic stabilization of the Canon C50, which does not have IBIS. Now the results of that test, and I think many of you agreed in the comments below, that the'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Panasonic IBIS is still generations ahead of the electronic stabilization that most cameras have, including the C50. But a lot of you commented on another post-production type of stabilization that I did not talk about in that video. And so I wanted to'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rectify that mistake and talk about it here in this video. And that is gyro flow. So what is gyro flow and how is it different than electronic stabilization or even IBIS? Well, IBIS is when there\'s an actual mechanism that is around the'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sensor that moves the sensor to compensate for the camera shake that\'s happening while you\'re hand holding the camera or walking. Electronic stabilization does the same thing, but instead of moving the sensor around, it actually just crops a little bit into'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the sensor and then moves it around digitally. This often results in some very weird digital artifacts that kind of ruin the image and so I don\'t really like to use electronic stabilization. But IBIS also has some issues where if you\'re walking or moving a little too'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quick, then the IBIS mechanism will actually reach the end points of where it can move and that becomes a little bit jerky and kind of ruins the image as well. So there\'s got to be a better way. And there is, and it\'s gyro flow. Maybe.'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s find out. Think of gyro as just a little bit of extra information on your video file that you can then use later to stabilize your footage. Recently Canon has started'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'putting gyro into all of the metadata in their Canon C400 and C50, both of which don\'t have IBIS. [music] And so you can actually access that gyro data and stabilize this footage in post. Gyro flow is actually a post-production'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'software where it takes your image and takes some metadata that the camera records directly onto the file that it can then read the movement and stabilize it in post. Now the nice thing about'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gyro flow is it\'s not baked in, so if there are some weird artifacts, you don\'t have to use it. And also you can change the strength of how much stabilization you actually want to put on the footage. So we went out and did a series of tests'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with the Canon C50 and then use the gyro data at different shutter angles to see which offers the best results. And then we also did some control tests where we did actually didn\'t use any stabilization at all. So let\'s get to'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those tests and then I\'ll comment on them at the end of this video. Now a lot of cameras don\'t have the gyro'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data built into the camera itself. And so there\'s a really cool new product that I learned about just a few weeks ago and it\'s this little guy right here. So this is a small gyroscope stabilizer from NeeYan and you can find it on'

[04:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Amazon for about 100 bucks. And what it does is you actually put it on top of your camera like this. And then you match the recording by pushing record for about 5 seconds and then again for 5 seconds so'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you have two files where they should match up pretty much exactly. And then you just push record on this device, let it run all day, and then when you put the two into the NeeYan software, it finds where the metadata should be going'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'onto your video files and automatically matches those up. And then you can put both of those into a gyro flow program to actually stabilize the footage. This is a really cool small device and it\'s'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to work very similarly to the C50\'s gyro. And I actually did a couple of shots where I shot with the C50 with the NeeYan on top. Now there are a couple limitations that'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I learned about and then in the field were confirmed when I was testing this out that come with the gyro metadata and the [music] gyroscope uh stabilizer that NeeYan makes. And that is that it doesn\'t work great when your shutter'

[05:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'angle is at 180° or basically double your frame rate when you\'re talking about shutter speed. So I often shoot at 24 frames per second and I\'ll shoot at a 180° shutter angle, which is 1/48 of a second shutter speed. That gives you'

[05:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that nice cinematic motion [music] blur that, you know, looks natural when you\'re waving in front of your hands, you can see the motion blur. You\'re not seeing a bunch of individual frames like you would if you had a faster [music] shutter speed. What I\'ve noticed and'

[05:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what other people on the internet have confirmed is that when you\'re shooting at a 180° shutter angle, that motion blur starts to become strange [music] digital artifacts when using gyro data. And so like in fine details on trees or'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leaves, you\'ll start seeing a little bit of jitter, almost like a strange noise pattern that is affecting your images. And so NeeYan and pretty much most people who use gyro recommend that you'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use a faster [music] shutter speed to eliminate a lot of those digital artifacts. Which means that if you\'re shooting on the C50, you\'re probably better off shooting at a 90° shutter angle or a 45° shutter angle, which again eliminates some of'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that motion blur, but it does give you much better results and you\'ll see that in [music] our tests. Now the one nice thing, though you lose some of that motion blur, a lot of post-production softwares like Premiere and DaVinci Resolve have different effects that you'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can apply to your footage to add some motion blur. So you could get the best of both worlds where you have that really stable footage through gyro data while also having that motion blur that makes your films feel natural. So as you can see from the test, obviously the'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'faster your shutter speed is or the lower your shutter angle, the better results that you get. So once you have your footage, you can put it into a gyro flow app and actually increase the strength or work with a bunch of'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different parameters to actually stabilize your footage. And you can even lock down that horizon level so that it stays the same even if you are moving the camera like crazy. And so that\'s the big advantage over electronic'

[07:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stabilization in camera or even IBIS, which whatever the camera gives you, that\'s what you get and it\'s baked into the file forever. But if I wanted that kind of cool handheld look, I could put the smoothness way down on the gyro flow app and that would allow me to get sort'

[07:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of a natural but not too shaky look. Whereas if I wanted to just float along like a gimbal, I can do that too. [music] That is a pretty impressive way to stabilize your footage. If you\'re'

[07:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shooting a feature film or a feature documentary, you might want to stick with stabilized lenses for a lot of your work, but have gyro flow is sort of is your backup in case things get a little too shaky. But if you\'re just out capturing b-roll for fun'

[07:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; or you just don\'t have a stabilizer on you and need to get a shot, then it\'s nice to know that you can always take that gyro data, put it into gyro flow, and stabilize the image. So for those of you who have a Canon C400 or a C50, [music] know that the gyro data is'

[08:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really, really useful, especially for getting shots when you don\'t have a stabilizer or a tripod on you. But for everyone else, I highly recommend checking out this little [music] box from NeeYan. I\'ll put a link in the description below. It\'s on Amazon, it\'s'

[08:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only 100 bucks. And [music] yes, you might have a Panasonic that has the best IBIS in the business, but you never know, you might be shooting with a larger cinema camera that doesn\'t have any stabilization or even a Sigma fp or smaller camera that could really use'

[08:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some extra stabilization. And so having this on hand, putting this in your bag, and just popping it out when you need it could be really, really useful. So check out the NeeYan gyroscope stabilizer and I hope you get stable images in your'

[08:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'future. All right, we\'ll see you in the next video.'
